    "answer_id" : 61618542,
    "question_id" : 29488900,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>The <code>-Dtest=*</code> command line option of Maven appears to trigger the show of stdout in unit tests.  </p>\n\n<p>By convention, the stdout shows in <code>target/surefire-reports/*-output.txt</code>. Apparently, the Surefire plugin developers could not reuse stdout for communication of many things between the tests and the framework.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4193275,
      "reputation" : 1013,
      "user_id" : 3435342,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/bKGbWKUr.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Steve Stilson",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3435342/steve-stilson"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1763162300,
    "creation_date" : 1763162300,
    "answer_id" : 79820498,
    "question_id" : 29488900,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I've had this same problem, where System.out.println()s from my Cucumber tests didn't show up in the output.  It turned out that the reason was because my Docker / Colima configuration was messed up, and Cucumber was having trouble spinning up a Docker image to run the Cucumber tests with.  So I dumped my images and reconstructed a clean Docker and Colima.  Then, the Cucumber tests proceeded without problems, and I saw the System.out.printlns in the log.</p>\n"
  } ],
